reference.unstructured: Freud defined these effects as “traumatic neurosis.” His writings on the subject began in 1915 with his “Thoughts for the Times of War and Death,” Standard Edition (SE) (London: Hogarth, 1953), 14: 289-300, continued in his “Introduction toPsycho-analysis and the War Neuroses,” published in 1919, SE (London: Hogarth, 1955), 17: 205-215, and culminated in “Beyond the Pleasure Principle,” published in 1920, SE (London: Hogarth, 1955), 18: 7-64. Freud presents trauma in these works as an outcome of external events, in opposition to his conceptualization of childhood traumas, which he claims emanate from internal threatening affects. Psychoanalytic literature has since extensively debated the relations between inner and outer sources of trauma. See, among others, Siegfried Zepf and Florian D. Zepf, “Trauma and Traumatic Neurosis: Freud's Concept Revisited,” International Journal of Psychoanalysis 89 (2008): 331-53.
